The PhD research project aims to provide fundamental knowledge on:
(i) The aerodynamics, power performance and wake interactions of wind turbines for layout optimization of VAWT wind farms in off-shore and urban areas;
(ii) The optimal geometry and positioning of building-integrated wind energy harvesting systems; 


Promoter: Prof. Dr. ir. B. Blocken, Co-promoter: Dr. ir. H. Montazeri, Daily supervisor: Dr. ir. A. Rezaeiha

The second year "Project 2 Building Physics & Structural Design" focuses on further expanding basic skills acquired in the first year by bachelor architecture students. These include skills in context and spatial analysis, drafting and finalizing a program of requirements related to the functioning of the building, demonstration of the performance of the building and the comfort perception of its users, and development of optimal plans and sections demonstrating the detailed and materialized realization of the building.

• Selected as teacher for this course, one of the core courses for 2nd year bachelor students;
• Designed and led weekly lectures and discussion sections for a group of 16 students;
• Designed course materials including design problems and assessment criteria;
• Educated the students on ventilation, daylight, thermal, visual and acoustic comfort, energy consumption, emission, embodied energy, sustainability, building-integrated photovoltaics (BIPV);
• Assessed and graded the final designs and reports of 16 students;
• Co-assessed the final designs and reports of 40 other bachelor students led by other teachers;
• Assisted faculty with administrative tasks regarding the course.

"BAU Studio 1" offers a first introduction to the full scope of the professional and academic field of the built environment. Students gain knowledge by doing three sets of assignments focused on use and planning (U-assignment), on urbanism and architecture (A-assignment), on structural design and building physics (B-assignment) and on general professional skills and skills in using media (Media & skills).

• Selected as teacher for this core course of first year bachelors;
• led weekly lectures and discussion sections for 3 groups of 13 students (39 in total) in span of 2 quartiles;
• Educated students on structural design and building physics and related concepts including daylight, structural integrity, sustainability and passive design;
• Assessed and graded the final designs and reports;
• Assisted faculty with administrative tasks regarding the course.

The 't Hool Eindhoven 1960 -> Energy neutral future 2050' bachelor end project offered by the Built Environment is the individual closure of the bachelor program in which the students show that they are able to execute a design or research project independently. 

• Co-supervised a group of 6 last-year bachelor students in analyzing the existing situation and planning the renovation of a 1960's dwelling in Woerden, Utrecht, the Netherlands;
• Co-directed the planning to focus on comfort, health and circularity under the overarching target of sustainability, to meet the goals of the project;
• Trained the students on high-fidelity daylight simulation and visual comfort assessment;
• Co-assessed the final designs and reports.

The 'Heat, air & moisture transfer' part of the course includes concepts and tools for moisture, radiation and convective transport mechanisms in building envelopes. Furthermore, the students gain experience in (i) calculating moisture performances of building constructions and (ii) developing and simulating models using Comsol and critically evaluating the results. The students learn to apply the calculation and simulation tools to evaluate the performance of building envelopes.
The 'CFD 2' part of this course provides advanced knowledge on CFD simulations and trains the students in performing high-quality CFD simulations. In the end, the students are able to (i) construct a computational geometry and mesh for CFD simulations of flow problems related to the built environment, (ii) perform high-quality CFD simulations of outdoor wind flow, indoor airflow, and wind-turbine flow problems and (iii) critically reflect on CFD simulations performed by others.

• Performed weekly live demonstrations on modeling, grid generation and CFD simulation for a group of 20 master students;
• Coached the students to follow the instructions and execute their own simulations;
• Assisted the students with troubleshooting their simulations;
• Tutored the students on how to analyze the results;
• Advised the students in writing the reports and presenting the results;
• Assisted in grading the final reports.

Architectural Design III is the main course for 3rd year bachelor students of architecture. In this course, the students design a public building (in this case a museum) during the semester, resulting in a final design and presentation. The students have to detect the success criteria for such a building function and try to meet them in their design.

• Designed and led weekly lectures and discussion sessions for a group of 14 students;
• Designed course materials including design problems and assessment criteria;
• Educated the students on physicals planning, functionality, technical drawing and aesthetics ;
• Assessed and graded the final designs;
• Co-assessed the final designs and reports of 40 other bachelor students led by other teachers;
• Assisted faculty with administrative tasks regarding the course.

In this course the students learn about different technologies and structures available to create architecture. The course includes tutoring on different structures and technologies, followed by hands-on model making to mimic these structures in smaller scales.

• Designed and led weekly lectures and discussion sessions for two groups of 14 students (28 in total);
• Designed course materials including design problems and assessment criteria;
• Educated the students on structural design and integrity ;
• Assessed and graded the final designs;
• Assisted faculty with administrative tasks regarding the course.

Architecture design project I (M.Sc. course) is the main course for 1st year master students of architecture. In this course, the students learn more about physical planning and design of larger buildings with more complicated requirements compared to their bachelor.

• Designed and led weekly lecture review and discussion sections for group of 25 master students;
• Carried out weekly design correction sessions with individual students;
• Tutored the students on how to analyze, troubleshoot and optimize their designs;
• Advised the students in writing their reports and presenting their designs;
• Assisted in grading the final reports.

Architecture design project I (M.Sc. course) is one of the main courses for 2nd year master students of architecture. In this course, the students learn about the different design phases of a building, different approaches to design and styles of different architects. Parallel to lectures, students work on a building and analyze its design process, resulting in a final report.

• Led weekly lecture review and discussion sections for group of 25 master students;
• Advised the students in writing and presenting their reports;
• Assisted in grading the final reports.

Applied Geometry is one of the two main courses for 1st semester bachelor students of architecture. In this course, the students understand how to use tools to draft technical drawing, develop their 2D/3D thinking, learn about symbols and signs in architectural drawings. The course also includes instructions to making architectural models.

• Carried out weekly lecture review and discussion sessions for group of 35 bachelor students;
• Carried out weekly design correction sessions with individual students;
• Tutored the students on how to use drawing tools and make models;
• Advised the students in their final project of technical drawings and architectural model;
• Assisted in grading the final projects.
